<br>
A person put to death has ZERO potential to committ another crime.<br>
<br>
A person given &quot;life without parole&quot; can still kill again, and some do.  Granted, it may be fellow inmates that get killed, but murder is still murder.<br>
<br>
A person given a number of years, or &quot;life&quot; has the potential to get out of prison.  Once out, they have the ability to kill again.<br>
<br>
If you actually believe that ZERO convicted murderers EVER kill again, then you could make the claim that death penalty doesn't prevent crime.  But the reality is the some do kill again, whether in prison or out in the community doesn't really matter.  <br>
<br>
As far as the $$ required to put a convicted murderer to death in Texas, it does seem like an outrageous amount.  But compare that amount to how much your families members life is worth.   Every time one of these convicted murderers kills again it is someone's family member, whether it be a fellow inmate, prison guard or just someone walking down the street. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uckorikkatorath.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ckorik Katorath</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 171<br> <font color=#E9D756>(7/22/02 12:07:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3475.topic&index=116>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: .</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> If you actually believe that ZERO convicted murderers EVER kill again, then you could make the claim that death penalty doesn't prevent crime. But the reality is the some do kill again, whether in prison or out in the community doesn't really matter. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
